title: Burnt out engineer looking to break free from his golden handcuffs
text:
As the title implies I’m a full stack engineer that’s looking to take a break from working for enterprise companies and reignite my passion for coding and life.

Ideally I’d like to quit sometime at the start of 2023 and travel, work on personal projects, and just be free for a bit from Jira tickets, and project managers.

I have 0 debt, and about 65k in reserves.

What I’m hoping to get are advice/inspiration/ideas from anyone whose done/doing the same thing. 1. How did you stay afloat financially without blowing through your savings? 2. Any general advice on things to look for or avoid during this time? Sorry if this vague sounding, I’m still figuring this out and just in general looking for inspiration. Thanks!

title: Ask HN: YouTube started recommending a bunch of Russian propoganda channels?
text:
Over the last few days my YouTube feed has started to fill up with Russian propoganda channels. I should note that I live in an Eastern European country that borders Russia. I do not speak Russian, and the only Russian YouTube channel I watch is the English version of Garage 54. My IP correctly identifies my country.

A few months ago I created a new Google account as my primary account was a Google Workspace account and I wanted to create a YouTube Premium Family, which you can't do with Workspace. I found some tools to copy my subscriptions over, and once I'd done that the new YouTube feed looked basically the same as the old account, just with a few repeated videos I'd seen as it didn't copy watched videos over. I disabled YouTube on the Workspace account so I made sure to use the right one. Since then everything has been great until this week.

Over the last few days my feed has started to have a bunch of Russian propoganda channels filling it. Usually the first five to ten videos are my subscriptions, then after that it's around 50% subscriptions and related and 50% random. The problem is the random videos are heavily weighted towards Russian propoganda, it's not the same as you see on the front page if you are logged out.

My YouTube watch history doesn't show anything unusual and I haven't logged into any devices that others have access to. Nobody in my home or Family watches Russian propoganda, and I don't think anyone at my office would. Whenever I see these videos I select 'Don't recommend channel' or 'Not interested', but YouTube is still recommending the same type of videos.

Any suggestions?
